    "question": "How do Salamanders breathe?",
    "model": "perplexity.ai",
    "date": "2023-04-10",
    "answer": "Salamanders can breathe through their gills, lungs, skin, mouth, and throat. The process of breathing can differ from type to type of salamanders. Some salamanders breathe through their gills, while others breathe through their lungs. Salamanders primarily rely on their skin for respiration, which is thin and permeable, allowing oxygen to diffuse into their bloodstream and carbon dioxide to diffuse out. Salamanders that live on land lose their gills as they grow older. Salamander larvae breathe through their gills, while adult salamanders such as the lungless salamanders breathe through their skin and the lining of their mouth, which is called buccopharyngeal respiration. [1][2][3][4][5]",
